<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910502-0127</DOCNO><DOCID>910502-0127.</DOCID><HL>   Comptroller Requests   Government Review   Of His Financial Deals</HL><DATE>05/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Comptroller of the Currency Robert Clarke,hoping to calm concerns about his personal investments, askedgovernment ethics officials to review his financial dealingsand determine if &quot;any further actions are appropriate.&quot;   The Washington Post disclosed Tuesday that Mr. Clarke, whosupervises 4,200 federally chartered banks, has activelytraded stocks and has bought and sold $1.7 million of &quot;junk&quot;bonds since becoming comptroller in 1985. Some of thetransactions were financed by bank loans. Mr. Clarke alsosits on the boards of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. andthe Resolution Trust Corp., the savings-and-loan cleanupagency that manages a huge portfolio of the high-risk,high-return junk bonds.</LP><TEXT>   In a statement, Mr. Clarke said that all of his financialtransactions had been fully disclosed to, and approved by,government ethics officers. Nevertheless, he said he isrequesting another review because &quot;I am, of course, concernedthat questions have been raised about my financialtransactions and holdings.&quot;   Separately, the FDIC said it had renewed a 1988 request tothe Office of Government Ethics for more authority to reviewthe comptroller's financial holdings for potential conflictsof interest. The earlier request wasn't acted on, an FDICofficial said.   Unlike some government officials, Mr. Clarke has chosen tomanage his own investments instead of placing them in a blindtrust.</TEXT></DOC>